\begin_layout Abstract
This article presents a new real-world optimization problem related to weather-aware irrigation scheduling.
 The problem is formulated as a continuous minimization task in which irrigation decisions are determined under weather-dependent water demand,
 rainfall effects,
 and nonlinear operational penalties.
 The proposed benchmark is designed to remain realistic while also being sufficiently challenging for numerical optimization.
 The article provides the full mathematical formulation of the problem,
 explains its main components and parameters,
 and reports an experimental study focused on its optimization behavior.
 From this perspective,
 the proposed problem is positioned within a clear framework for the study of real-world continuous optimization problems,
 offering an additional case in which mathematical formulation,
 practical interpretation,
 and experimental investigation coexist in a coherent and systematic manner.
\end_layout

