\begin_layout Standard
The proposed benchmark is motivated by the need to represent irrigation scheduling as a genuinely coupled seasonal decision process rather than as a separable stage-wise water allocation rule.
 In realistic irrigation environments,
 the amount of water applied at one stage influences not only the immediate water balance of the crop,
 but also subsequent storage,
 drainage,
 evaporative losses,
 and the cumulative preservation of seasonal productivity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Allen,Doorenbos,Wang,Linker,Li,Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This makes the domain naturally suitable for benchmark construction aimed at non-separable and state-dependent continuous optimization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark is intentionally synthetic in the sense that all exogenous profiles are generated analytically,
 yet it remains literature-informed in its semantic structure.
 Classical crop evapotranspiration concepts,
 weather-dependent irrigation demand,
 and yield-response-to-water ideas are preserved,
 whereas additional oscillatory,
 thresholded,
 and deceptive mechanisms are embedded to prevent rapid convergence to the best region.
 As a result,
 the problem should be interpreted as a new benchmark problem with agronomic meaning,
 not as a calibrated digital twin of a particular field or crop system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mathematical Formulation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Formulation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $D\geq4$
\end_inset

 denote the problem dimension,
 and let
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=(x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{D})^{\mathsf{T}}$
\end_inset

 be the decision vector,
 where
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the irrigation depth (mm) applied at stage 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 of a synthetic growing season.
 The feasible set is the hyper-rectangle
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega=[0,80]^{D},\qquad0\leq x_{i}\leq80,\qquad i=1,\ldots,D.
\]

\end_inset

 The season length is fixed at
\begin_inset Formula $120$
\end_inset

 days,
 so the stage duration is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta t=\frac{120}{D},
\]

\end_inset

 and the normalized stage coordinate is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{i}=\frac{i}{D+1},\qquad i=1,\ldots,D.
\]

\end_inset

 Recommended difficult dimensions are 
\begin_inset Formula $D\in\{24,30,50,70,100\}$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

 suitable for routine experiments and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 producing substantially harder landscapes for population-based optimizers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make the benchmark deterministic and self-contained,
 all exogenous weather and crop coefficients are generated analytically from 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The stage-wise profiles are defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ETo_{i}=2.8+3.2\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Kc_{i}=0.55+0.65\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
rain_{i}=8+18\cos^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Ky_{i}=0.85+0.55\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
heat_{i}=0.40+0.60\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
wind_{i}=0.35+0.65\cos^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
tariff_{i}=0.90+0.18\sin(2\pi s_{i}+0.20),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{base,i}=0.78+0.10\cos(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho_{i}=0.52+0.18\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i}^{max}=50+20\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
freq_{i}=0.22+0.09\sin(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi_{i}=0.70i+0.30\sin(2\pi s_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 The crop evapotranspiration demand follows the standard evapotranspiration-based construction
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
ETc_{i}=ETo_{i}Kc_{i}\Delta t,
\]

\end_inset

 which grounds the benchmark in classical irrigation science [4].
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $Ky_{i}$
\end_inset

 is used as a stage sensitivity factor in the relative yield-preservation component,
 consistent with the general idea of yield response to water stress 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first major source of difficulty is local decision coupling.
 A neighbor-coupled hydraulic load is introduced as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N_{i}=0.60x_{i}+0.25x_{i-1}+0.15x_{i+1},
\]

\end_inset

 with boundary conventions 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}=x_{D+1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Effective irrigation efficiency is then defined by the oscillatory nonlinear law
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\eta_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})=\eta_{base,i}\Big[1-0.22\sin^{2}(freq_{i}x_{i}+\phi_{i})-0.10\sin^{2}(0.07N_{i}+0.50\phi_{i})\Big],
\]

\end_inset

 clipped to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.45,1.00]$
\end_inset

,
 and the effective irrigation becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I_{i}^{eff}=\eta_{i}(\boldsymbol{x})x_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 These oscillatory factors are synthetic ruggedness generators.
 They are not intended to claim precise field physics;
 they are introduced to generate repeated attraction basins and to make coordinate-wise search substantially less effective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second major source of difficulty is path dependence through a synthetic soil-water storage state 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The initial storage is fixed by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{1}=0.35S_{1}^{max}.
\]

\end_inset

 The total water available at stage
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{i}=rain_{i}+I_{i}^{eff}+0.55S_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the stage deficit and surplus are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
deficit_{i}=\max(0,ETc_{i}-A_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
surplus_{i}=\max(0,A_{i}-ETc_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 Deep drainage is modeled by the thresholded term
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
deep_{i}=\max(0,surplus_{i}-0.35S_{i}^{max})\Big[0.55+0.20wind_{i}+0.15\sin^{2}(0.11x_{i}+\phi_{i})\Big],
\]

\end_inset

 recharge is defined as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
recharge_{i}=\rho_{i}\max(0,surplus_{i}-deep_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 evaporative loss is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
evaploss_{i}=(0.08+0.10heat_{i}+0.04wind_{i})S_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the storage transition is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i+1}=\mathrm{clip}\Big(0.82S_{i}+recharge_{i}-evaploss_{i},\,0,\,S_{i}^{max}\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 This recursion makes the objective stateful:
 changing one variable can alter the effective optimization landscape seen by many subsequent variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A multiplicative relative yield-preservation term is included to prevent the problem from collapsing into a pure cost minimization model.
 The relative water-satisfaction ratio is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{i}=\min\Big(1,\frac{A_{i}}{ETc_{i}+\varepsilon}\Big),\qquad\varepsilon=10^{-12},
\]

\end_inset

 the stage stress is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
stress_{i}=1-r_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the stage contribution to yield preservation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{i}=\mathrm{clip}\Big(1-Ky_{i}stress_{i}^{1.35}-0.08heat_{i}\exp\Big(-\frac{A_{i}}{0.35ETc_{i}+1}\Big),\,0.02,\,1\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 The season-level relative yield factor is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{rel}=\prod_{i=1}^{D}y_{i}.
\]

\end_inset

 The multiplicative construction is deliberate:
 a few severely stressed stages can dominate many small local improvements,
 which makes the global tradeoff structure significantly more deceptive than in additive reward formulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doorenbos,Linker,Li,Zhao"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark is posed as the minimization problem
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\min_{\boldsymbol{x}\in[0,80]^{D}}f(\boldsymbol{x}),
\]

\end_inset

 where
\size footnotesize

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\boldsymbol{x})=C_{water}+C_{pump}+P_{def}+P_{exc}+P_{smooth}+P_{res}+P_{int}+P_{win}+P_{term}+P_{budget}+P_{peak}-350Y_{rel}.
\]

\end_inset


\size default
 The water-cost term is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{water}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}tariff_{i}x_{i},
\]

\end_inset

 and the pumping-cost term is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{pump}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}0.0045N_{i}^{2}\Big[1+0.35\sin^{2}(0.08x_{i}+0.60\phi_{i})\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 A weather-modulated shock factor is introduced by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
shock_{i}=1+0.18heat_{i}\sin^{2}(0.09x_{i}+1.3wind_{i}+\phi_{i}),
\]

\end_inset

 and the deficit and excess penalties are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{def}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}(0.12+0.06heat_{i})deficit_{i}^{2}shock_{i},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{exc}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}(0.05+0.05wind_{i})\Big(deep_{i}^{2}+0.30surplus_{i}^{2}\Big).
\]

\end_inset

 Temporal roughness and local resonance are imposed by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{smooth}=\sum_{i=2}^{D}(0.06+0.02wind_{i})(x_{i}-x_{i-1})^{2},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{res}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}8.0(1+0.70heat_{i})\sin^{2}(freq_{i}x_{i}+\phi_{i}).
\]

\end_inset

 Neighbor-stage overloading and bilinear coupling are represented by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{int}=\sum_{i=2}^{D}\Big[0.018\max(0,x_{i}+0.55x_{i-1}-58)^{2}+0.025x_{i}x_{i-1}\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 A deceptive preferred-window term is defined through
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{i}=18+26\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i}),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{win}=\sum_{i=1}^{D}\Big(0.014+0.010\sin^{2}(\pi s_{i})\Big)(x_{i}-\mu_{i})^{2}\Big[1+0.40\sin^{2}(0.06x_{i}+\phi_{i})\Big].
\]

\end_inset

 The terminal storage penalty is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{term}=1.2\Big(S_{D+1}-0.45S_{D}^{max}\Big)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 the soft seasonal budget penalty uses
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{D}=28D,
\]

\end_inset

 and is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{budget}=0.010\Big(\sum_{i=1}^{D}x_{i}-B_{D}\Big)^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 while the peak-load penalty is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{peak}=0.035\sum_{i=1}^{D}\max(0,N_{i}-62)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

 The complete problem is therefore a box-constrained,
 deterministic,
 strongly non-separable,
 rugged,
 and partially nonsmooth minimization benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No closed-form global optimum is assumed known.
 This is intentional and is part of the benchmark design.
 The objective contains repeated oscillatory structures,
 threshold-triggered regime changes,
 clipped internal states,
 recursive storage dynamics,
 multiplicative stage aggregation,
 and coupled penalties.
 Consequently,
 the landscape contains many local minima and deceptive tradeoffs,
 and performance cannot be inferred from low-dimensional intuition alone.
 From the perspective of benchmark design,
 the difficulty comes from the simultaneous presence of six mechanisms:
 recursive state propagation,
 local oscillatory efficiency modulation,
 thresholded drainage and peak penalties,
 multiplicative yield aggregation,
 neighbor coupling through 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 and soft preferred-window structure that competes with the remaining terms instead of revealing the optimum.
 For these reasons,
 the benchmark is substantially harder than a smooth irrigation cost-yield tradeoff model while remaining interpretable as a weather-coupled irrigation scheduling problem.
\end_layout

