\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Full problem formulation (
\begin_inset Formula $ALL$
\end_inset

).

\series default
 The results for the complete benchmark reveal a strongly differentiated performance landscape across both methods and dimensions.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

,
 the methods mlshaderl and jso emerge as the most reliable solvers,
 achieving empirical success rates of 100% and 90%,
 respectively,
 both converging to the reference best value of approximately 1962.57.
 The method arq attains the same best value with a success rate of 67%,
 while cmaes reaches it in 17% of runs.
 The remaining three solvers clpso,
 ga,
 and gwo either fail to reach the reference best value consistently or exhibit substantially higher mean objective values,
 indicating premature convergence to suboptimal regions.
 The standard deviations for mlshaderl and jso are negligibly small,
 while ga and gwo display standard deviations exceeding 80 and 98 units,
 respectively,
 reflecting high run-to-run variability and a lack of reliable convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the dimension increases to 
\begin_inset Formula $D=30$
\end_inset

,
 the overall picture changes substantially.
 mlshaderl retains a high success rate of 63%,
 and both jso and acor achieve rates of 43% and 60%,
 respectively.
 All three solvers converge to the same reference best value of approximately 2010.32,
 confirming that this local attractor is reachable from different algorithmic trajectories.
 By contrast,
 ga and gwo continue to perform poorly,
 with ga reporting a mean of 2370.93 against a best value of 2198.68,
 indicating that the vast majority of its runs terminate far from the best feasible region.
 The standard deviation of ga exceeds 116 units,
 which is roughly 20 times larger than those of the better-performing methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

,
 the difficulty of the benchmark increases markedly.
 acor now achieves the highest success rate (83%),
 followed by mlshaderl (73%) and jso (37%).
 Notably,
 arq also converges to the reference best value but only in 13% of runs,
 reflecting a moderate but unreliable performance at this scale.
 The cmaes method,
 which performed reasonably at lower dimensions,
 drops to a success rate of 3% and a mean of 3785.72,
 indicating that its search dynamics become misaligned with the rugged structure of the problem at moderate dimensionality.
 The clpso and gwo methods show similarly poor reliability,
 with success rates of 3% and their mean values deviating substantially from the best observed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

,
 the distinction between robust and fragile solvers becomes even more pronounced.
 The jso and mlshaderl methods continue to locate the best-known solution,
 with success rates of 60% and 23%,
 respectively.
 The acor method achieves a success rate of 17% at this dimension.
 All other methods arq,
 clpso,
 cmaes,
 ga,
 and gwo obtain success rates of 3%,
 indicating near-complete failure to reliably reproduce the best solution.
 Particularly striking is the gap between the best observed values and the mean values for cmaes (5712.10 vs.
 5774.91),
 ga (6052.12 vs.
 6184.06),
 and gwo (5902.42 vs.
 5975.72),
 suggesting that even the rare successful runs for these methods are followed by a majority of runs trapped in inferior regions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the most challenging setting,
 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 the success rates of all methods collapse.
 arq achieves the highest rate (17%),
 followed by mlshaderl (13%).
 The remaining six methods attain rates of 3% or lower.
 Notably,
 cmaes exhibits the most severe deterioration,
 with a mean of 9084.51 against a best value of 8715.90,
 and a standard deviation of 227.76 by far the largest observed across all methods and dimensions in this variant indicating a highly inconsistent search behavior in large-dimensional settings.
 The jso method,
 which performs well up to 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

,
 also degrades significantly at
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 achieving only a 3% success rate.
 This confirms that the combined presence of recursive state dynamics,
 oscillatory efficiency modulation,
 multiplicative yield aggregation,
 and neighbor coupling creates a landscape that becomes exponentially harder to navigate as the number of decision variables grows.
\end_layout

