,
 confirming that the preferred-window term acts as a genuine penalty that shifts the global optimum relative to the attractors created by the remaining terms.
 The relatively large standard deviations observed for jso (SD = 206.06) and arq (SD = 202.09) at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

 suggest that,
 in the absence of the preferred-window structure,
 some runs are attracted to qualitatively different regions of the landscape,
 increasing the variance of outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cross-variant and cross-method synthesis.

\series default
 Taken together,
 the ablation study reveals that the difficulty of the proposed benchmark is genuinely multi-mechanism in character.
 No single ablation removes all difficulty:
 even the removal of the most impactful mechanism (oscillatory efficiency) leaves a landscape that is challenging at 
\begin_inset Formula $D\geq50$
\end_inset

 for several methods.
 The methods mlshaderl and acor consistently outperform the other six solvers across all variants and dimensions,
 suggesting that their adaptive parameter control and archive-based memory mechanisms are particularly well matched to the coupled,
 rugged structure of the irrigation benchmark.
 The methods ga and gwo perform poorly in the full formulation and improve only moderately under single-mechanism ablations,
 indicating that they are fundamentally limited by the combined presence of non-separability,
 state recursion,
 and oscillatory structure.
 The dimension scaling behavior observed across all variants confirms the expected superlinear growth in difficulty,
 with the transition from 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

 representing the most critical threshold at which the majority of solvers lose reliable convergence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experimental results reported in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:experiments"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 invite interpretation at three distinct levels:
 the performance profile of the competing solvers on the full benchmark,
 the structural information supplied by the ablation study,
 and the broader implications of both for the design and use of real-world-inspired continuous optimization benchmarks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most salient observation across all five dimensions of the full benchmark is the consistent superiority of mlshaderl and acor over the remaining six methods.
 This outcome is not incidental.
 Both methods employ mechanisms adaptive differential evolution with historical archive management in mlshaderl,
 and continuous ant colony optimization with probability density estimation in acor that provide implicit memory of previously explored regions and allow the search distribution to contract toward promising basins without premature commitment.
 In a landscape characterized by recursive state dependence,
 repeated local oscillatory structure,
 and multiplicative coupling between stages,
 these capabilities are precisely what distinguish reliable convergence from stagnation.
 By contrast,
 methods such as ga and gwo,
 which rely on simpler population recombination or swarm attraction heuristics,
 consistently fail to maintain sufficient diversity in the presence of the benchmark's multiple deceptive attractors,
 as evidenced by their large standard deviations even at moderate dimensions.
 The dimension scaling behavior observed in the full formulation is consistent with the combinatorial growth of non-separable interactions.
 The critical transition appears between 
\begin_inset Formula $D=50$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

,
 where the majority of solvers lose reliable convergence and their success rates collapse toward the minimum observable value of 3%.
 This transition is not merely a manifestation of the curse of dimensionality in the generic sense:
 it reflects the fact that the recursive storage propagation,
 which links the effective landscape seen by variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 to decisions made at all preceding stages 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{i-1}$
\end_inset

,
 creates an effective dependency chain whose length grows linearly with 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 increases,
 the probability that a randomly initialized trajectory can locate and remain in the correct basin across all stages simultaneously diminishes rapidly,
 making global search substantially harder than dimension alone would suggest for a separable or smoothly non-separable problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ablation protocol,
 which isolates the contribution of each embedded difficulty mechanism by selectively disabling it,
 reveals a hierarchy of mechanism importance that is both informative and practically useful.
 The oscillatory efficiency mechanism emerges as the single most consequential source of landscape ruggedness:
 its removal enables multiple solvers to achieve success rates near or at 100% even at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

,
 a result that is unattainable in the full formulation at that dimension.
 This finding has a clear structural interpretation.
 The oscillatory modulation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}(\mathbf{x})$
\end_inset

,
 which depends on both the local decision 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the neighbor-coupled load 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 introduces a dense lattice of local attractors that are energetically competitive with the global basin.
 In the absence of this mechanism,
 the residual landscape formed by the water cost,
 pumping cost,
 deficit and excess penalties,
 and terminal storage term is sufficiently smooth to permit gradient-like local improvement strategies to succeed over repeated restarts.
 The ablation of multiplicative yield aggregation produces the second most pronounced improvement in solver performance,
 particularly at 
\begin_inset Formula $D=70$
\end_inset

 where the success rate of arq rises to 100% from 3% in the full formulation.
 This confirms the theoretical expectation that a multiplicative 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i}y_{i}$
\end_inset

 structure is more deceptive than an additive one:
 a single stage with near-zero yield contribution suppresses the entire seasonal productivity,
 creating a highly nonlinear global tradeoff that cannot be resolved by improving individual stages in isolation.
 The removal of recursive storage produces intermediate improvements,
 while the removal of neighbor coupling,
 threshold losses,
 and preferred-window regularization each contributes more modestly to overall difficulty.
 This ordering suggests that the benchmark's hardness is primarily driven by local landscape ruggedness and global aggregation structure,
 rather than by the connectivity patterns or regularization terms.
 Crucially,
 no single ablation restores the problem to the triviality of the fully simplified variant,
 and the combination of any two residual mechanisms is already sufficient to produce non-trivial landscapes at higher dimensions.
 This multi-mechanism character is precisely what the benchmark is designed to capture,
 and the ablation evidence confirms that the design achieves its intent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed benchmark addresses a recognized gap at the intersection of two research communities.
 Within continuous global optimization,
 the dominant benchmark suites  including the CEC and BBOB families are composed primarily of synthetic analytical functions whose difficulty is controlled through transformation,
 rotation,
 and shifting,
 but which lack the semantic interpretability and state-dependent coupling of physically motivated problems.
 Within agricultural water management and irrigation scheduling,
 the available simulation-optimization frameworks are calibrated to specific field conditions and crop models and are therefore neither self-contained nor designed to be difficult for optimization algorithms per se.
 The present benchmark occupies a complementary position:
 it is analytically self-contained and fully deterministic,
 requires no external data,
 exhibits a rich and verifiable difficulty structure through the ablation protocol,
 and retains an agronomic interpretation that makes its components meaningful beyond pure algorithmic testing.
 The deliberate absence of a known closed-form global optimum further distinguishes it from classical synthetic benchmarks,
 making it a genuine black-box problem for which algorithmic progress can only be measured empirically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:conclusions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This article has introduced a new continuous global optimization benchmark derived from the semantics of weather-coupled irrigation scheduling.
 The benchmark is formulated as a deterministic,
 box-constrained minimization problem in which the objective function integrates a recursive soil-water storage state,
 an oscillatory irrigation efficiency law,
 a multiplicative seasonal yield factor,
 neighbor-coupled hydraulic penalties,
 threshold-triggered drainage losses,
 and a deceptive preferred-window regularization term.
 The problem is analytically self-contained:
 all exogenous weather and crop profiles are generated from the normalized stage coordinate,
 requiring no external datasets.
 Recommended problem dimensions span from 
\begin_inset Formula $D=24$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $D=100$
\end_inset

,
 with the transition from moderate to high dimensionality producing a substantial and predictable increase in landscape difficulty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experimental study,
 conducted over 30 independent runs of eight established continuous optimizers across all recommended dimensions and eight problem variants,
 yields three principal conclusions.
 First,
 the full benchmark presents a genuinely multi-mechanism difficulty that no single state-of-the-art solver reliably resolves at 
\begin_inset Formula $D\geq70$
\end_inset

:
 even the best-performing methods,
 mlshaderl and acor,
 achieve success rates below 25% at the highest dimension tested.
 Second,
 the ablation study identifies oscillatory efficiency modulation as the dominant source of landscape ruggedness,
 with multiplicative yield aggregation as the second most impactful mechanism;
 together,
 these two components account for the majority of the difficulty gap between the full and the simplified formulations.
 Third,
 the fully simplified variant,
 in which all embedded difficulty mechanisms are disabled,
 is solved to optimality by most methods across all dimensions,
 confirming that the observed difficulty in the full formulation is structural rather than numerical in origin.
 These results collectively validate the proposed benchmark as a meaningful and scalable tool for studying continuous optimization algorithms on non-separable,
 stateful,
 and rugged landscapes with a clear real-world interpretation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several directions of investigation emerge naturally from the present work and are left for future research.
 The current formulation employs a single synthetic weather profile generated from trigonometric functions of the normalized stage coordinate.
 A natural extension would introduce a parameterized family of profiles indexed,
 for instance,
 by the amplitude of the evapotranspiration cycle,
 the frequency of the rainfall component,
 or the magnitude of the tariff oscillation producing a suite of benchmark instances with controlled variability in the exogenous driving signals.
 Such a family would allow researchers to study how algorithm performance varies with the statistical properties of the weather input,
 a question of direct relevance to robust irrigation planning under forecast uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further generalization of considerable interest would introduce stochastic weather realizations,
 replacing the fixed analytical profiles with samples from a probability distribution calibrated to realistic seasonal variability.
 In this setting,
 the optimization problem becomes one of finding a decision vector that minimizes expected cost or maximizes robustness against worst-case scenarios,
 connecting the benchmark to the literature on stochastic and distributionally robust optimization.
 The recursive storage structure of the benchmark makes it particularly well suited for comparison with scenario-based and chance-constrained formulations.
 Along a related but distinct axis,
 the assumption that all irrigation decisions are made simultaneously at the beginning of the season could be relaxed.
 A dynamic extension,
 in which decisions are made sequentially with partial or noisy observations of the storage state between stages,
 would transform the benchmark into a sequential decision problem amenable to reinforcement learning,
 model predictive control,
 and Bayesian optimization methods,
 substantially broadening the community of researchers for whom the benchmark is relevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the benchmark is analytically defined and differentiable almost everywhere with the exception of the clipping and max operations it is also tractable for surrogate-assisted and gradient-based solvers,
 provided that subgradients or automatic differentiation are employed to handle the nonsmooth components.
 A systematic comparison of gradient-based methods,
 surrogate models,
 and derivative-free global optimizers on the same benchmark instances would provide empirical evidence on the trade-offs between first-order information exploitation and global exploration capacity in rugged,
 stateful landscapes.
 Complementing this direction,
 future work could apply established exploratory landscape analysis features such as fitness distance correlation,
 information content,
 and gradient homogeneity measures to the full and ablated formulations across all recommended dimensions.
 Such an analysis would provide a data-driven characterization of how each difficulty mechanism shapes the search landscape and would connect the benchmark's properties to the broader landscape analysis literature,
 enabling more principled algorithm selection and configuration.
 Finally,
 the current formulation uses soft penalties to encode operational constraints such as the seasonal water budget and the peak hydraulic load.
 A future variant that introduces hard constraints on total water use or on per-stage application rates would transform the benchmark into a constrained continuous optimization problem,
 enabling comparison with constraint-handling techniques including penalty methods,
 feasibility-rule approaches,
 and augmented Lagrangian strategies,
 and further expanding the benchmark's utility as a testing ground for modern continuous optimization methodology.
\end_layout

